we have to get on the same page about what a loot box is.

30
00:01:18,233 --> 00:01:21,615
And I think that question is a little harder than it appears at first.

31
00:01:22,775 --> 00:01:26,937
Most of us have an idea of what a loot box is in our mind.

32
00:01:27,177 --> 00:01:31,519
We might think of the stereotypical, you pay money or some green gems for a box

33
00:01:31,559 --> 00:01:32,840
that has some randomized items.

34
00:01:33,680 --> 00:01:37,922
But the truth is, there's a lot of chance involved in everything we do in life.

35
00:01:38,643 --> 00:01:41,304
And I could argue that anything on this screen is a loot box.

36
00:01:42,084 --> 00:01:43,725
I'm not going to go through each of these items,

37
00:01:43,805 --> 00:01:46,145
but I want to point out a couple of the items that

38
00:01:46,165 --> 00:01:46,866
are on this screen.

39
00:01:47,466 --> 00:01:48,806
In the middle there, you see just sort

40
00:01:48,826 --> 00:01:50,387
of a procedurally generated monster.

41
00:01:50,667 --> 00:01:52,648
We've had these in games for decades.

42
00:01:53,648 --> 00:01:56,329
And the mechanics are actually very similar to a loot box.

43
00:01:56,669 --> 00:01:58,770
The player gets a random assortment of items.

44
00:01:59,430 --> 00:02:00,991
Most of the time, those items are bad.

45
00:02:01,211 --> 00:02:02,391
Sometimes they're really good.

46
00:02:02,411 --> 00:02:05,992
And so there's some similarities there.

47
00:02:06,092 --> 00:02:08,133
Loot boxes really aren't that different from something

48
00:02:08,153 --> 00:02:09,353
we've been doing for a long time.

49
00:02:10,695 --> 00:02:12,135
What about that last example, right?

50
00:02:12,575 --> 00:02:14,816
I call a car a loot box, right?

51
00:02:14,836 --> 00:02:17,697
Let's say I invest in Bitcoin and I hold all that Bitcoin

52
00:02:17,737 --> 00:02:20,678
until I can afford my Lambo and I go to the dealership

53
00:02:20,978 --> 00:02:21,858
and the dealer says to me,

54
00:02:21,878 --> 00:02:23,119
do you want the extended warranty?

55
00:02:23,439 --> 00:02:25,039
And I say, no, I wanna save that money

56
00:02:25,079 --> 00:02:26,300
to invest in more Bitcoin.

57
00:02:26,840 --> 00:02:29,861
And 366 days later, my drive train blows out.

58
00:02:30,461 --> 00:02:31,701
I'm out half a million bucks.

59
00:02:32,422 --> 00:02:33,742
But no one is trying to say that

60
00:02:34,122 --> 00:02:35,723
I have to take the extended warranty.

61
00:02:36,023 --> 00:02:37,703
No one's trying to regulate that practice,

62
00:02:37,743 --> 00:02:39,424
but we face chance in everything we do.

63
00:02:40,840 --> 00:02:43,080
And because it's so hard to define what a loot box is,

64
00:02:43,860 --> 00:02:46,401
the answer to what a loot box is in today's presentation

65
00:02:46,481 --> 00:02:48,222
is it depends on the regulator.

66
00:02:49,462 --> 00:02:52,503
We see regulators governing loot boxes in different ways.

67
00:02:53,243 --> 00:02:54,543
And that's because I don't really

68
00:02:54,583 --> 00:02:57,764
think loot boxes are a problem in the game development

69
00:02:57,804 --> 00:02:58,244
industry.

70
00:02:58,604 --> 00:03:01,125
But I do think some loot boxes are

71
00:03:01,165 --> 00:03:03,345
symbolic of some very real issues we face.

72
00:03:04,884 --> 00:03:07,008
I think some loot boxes create compulsion loops.

73
00:03:07,469 --> 00:03:11,197
These are skinner box mechanics that keep players playing much longer than they actually

74
00:03:11,217 --> 00:03:11,658
want to play.

75
00:03:12,861 --> 00:03:15,083
Some loot boxes are symbolic of pay-to-win mechanics,

76
00:03:15,203 --> 00:03:16,283
where players feel like they're not

77
00:03:16,303 --> 00:03:18,005
being rewarded for their time or their skill,

78
00:03:18,045 --> 00:03:19,125
but just the money they put in.

79
00:03:19,766 --> 00:03:22,668
Some loot boxes are used in outright fraud,

80
00:03:23,569 --> 00:03:26,010
and a lot of loot boxes aren't transparent.

81
00:03:26,311 --> 00:03:29,293
It's not clear to the user what they're going to get

82
00:03:29,333 --> 00:03:30,253
and what their odds are.

83
00:03:30,273 --> 00:03:32,775
And so when we see loot boxes regulated,

84
00:03:32,855 --> 00:03:35,417
we actually see them targeting these four other practices.

85
00:03:36,895 --> 00:03:38,657
So with that, let's start with the United States.

86
00:03:39,357 --> 00:03:41,339
Now, the United States gets a reputation

87
00:03:42,040 --> 00:03:44,221
as a country where corporations make all the rules

88
00:03:44,382 --> 00:03:45,703
and there's no consumer protection.

89
00:03:46,303 --> 00:03:48,765
And in the case of loot boxes, that's absolutely right.

90
00:03:49,546 --> 00:03:52,388
There is no government organization, no agency,

91
00:03:52,749 --> 00:03:55,911
none of the 50 states that place any formal rules

92
00:03:56,251 --> 00:03:57,372
on the use of loot boxes.

93
00:03:58,373 --> 00:03:59,654
But there actually are some rules

94
00:03:59,694 --> 00:04:01,456
on the use of loot boxes in the United States,

95
00:04:01,476 --> 00:04:02,717
and those come from private companies.

96
00:04:03,443 --> 00:04:06,405
Those companies are the ESRB, that's the ratings organization

97
00:04:06,445 --> 00:04:09,266
here in the United States, and Apple through the App Store.

98
00:04:09,306 --> 00:04:12,048
If you have a mobile game that you're selling on iOS devices,

99
00:04:12,649 --> 00:04:14,330
Apple has rules you're going to have to comply with.

100
00:04:15,290 --> 00:04:16,471
I'll put a little asterisk here.

101
00:04:16,771 --> 00:04:19,193
That doesn't mean you can just commit outright fraud.

102
00:04:19,773 --> 00:04:22,475
If you're lying to your consumers, that's illegal.

103
00:04:22,495 --> 00:04:25,717
And that's been illegal for over a century, centuries,

104
00:04:25,897 --> 00:04:26,697
very long time.

105
00:04:26,717 --> 00:04:30,420
So don't use this as an excuse to do otherwise illegal things.

106
00:04:30,480 --> 00:04:32,541
But there's no specific loot box regulation.

107
00:04:34,065 --> 00:04:36,086
So let's talk about those private company rules.

108
00:04:36,966 --> 00:04:41,309
So for Apple, you must disclose the odds by item type.

109
00:04:41,389 --> 00:04:44,131
And Apple defines loot boxes as mechanisms

110
00:04:44,151 --> 00:04:46,632
that provide randomized virtual items for purchase.

111
00:04:47,653 --> 00:04:49,874
So Apple's sort of, there's three requirements

112
00:04:49,934 --> 00:04:51,015
to be in the loot box bucket.

113
00:04:51,655 --> 00:04:54,457
Has to be virtual item, has to be randomized,

114
00:04:54,537 --> 00:04:55,597
and has to be for purchase.

115
00:04:56,258 --> 00:04:57,478
I think that sort of lines up

116
00:04:57,518 --> 00:04:59,320
with most of our notions of loot boxes.

117
00:05:01,043 --> 00:05:02,864
And when I say disclosed by item type,

118
00:05:03,585 --> 00:05:05,647
what I mean by that is think of sort of the classic game

119
00:05:05,667 --> 00:05:07,348
that has a common item, rare item,

120
00:05:07,468 --> 00:05:08,969
an epic item, and a legendary item.

121
00:05:09,390 --> 00:05:10,331
That's what I mean by type.

122
00:05:10,471 --> 00:05:12,592
You don't have to list every single item

123
00:05:12,993 --> 00:05:14,694
and the odds of getting each and every item,

124
00:05:15,135 --> 00:05:16,916
but you have to list them by categories

125
00:05:17,036 --> 00:05:19,078
when you're selling on the App Store.

126
00:05:20,639 --> 00:05:21,500
What about ESRB?

127
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,242
How does the ratings organization define loot boxes?

128
00:05:24,462 --> 00:05:25,303
Well, they sort of don't.

129
00:05:25,783 --> 00:05:28,366
They lump loot boxes in with any in-game purchase.

130
00:05:29,907 --> 00:05:34,589
And the requirement for ESRB is that you include an in-game purchases label underneath your

131
00:05:34,629 --> 00:05:34,890
rating.

132
00:05:35,270 --> 00:05:37,511
I put an example up there in the lower right-hand corner.

133
00:05:38,171 --> 00:05:40,532
That's what the in-game purchases tab looks like.

134
00:05:40,952 --> 00:05:42,513
And that's an effort for transparency.

135
00:05:43,574 --> 00:05:45,475
The people who use ratings most are parents.

136
00:05:45,855 --> 00:05:49,677
And what parents care most about is how much is their child going to spend in the game.

137
00:05:50,117 --> 00:05:53,558
And they want to know if their child is going to spend more money.

138
00:05:53,819 --> 00:05:57,460
They don't really care that it's in the format of a loot box or a randomized capacity.

139
00:05:59,998 --> 00:06:01,599
So now I'm going to break us into a hypothetical.

140
00:06:01,819 --> 00:06:05,141
I find it's easier to think about these ideas in a context

141
00:06:05,181 --> 00:06:08,103
that might be more similar to the one you would face in your

142
00:06:08,123 --> 00:06:09,844
own company as a developer or publisher.

143
00:06:10,224 --> 00:06:11,805
It's not going to be particularly complicated.

144
00:06:12,265 --> 00:06:14,926
But in our hypothetical today, we have a game developer,

145
00:06:14,966 --> 00:06:17,688
ShadyCorp, and they're releasing a game, Drawn Out

146
00:06:17,748 --> 00:06:21,530
Chess, and this is a classic game of chess, but it's

147
00:06:21,690 --> 00:06:24,812
monetized by selling skins, specifically selling skins

148
00:06:24,832 --> 00:06:25,612
through loot boxes.

149
00:06:26,553 --> 00:06:28,635
They release the games with no disclosures,

150
00:06:28,795 --> 00:06:30,356
no consideration of the regulations.

151
00:06:31,077 --> 00:06:33,078
And a month later, an employee spots the issue.

152
00:06:33,699 --> 00:06:34,619
This actually happens a lot.

153
00:06:34,800 --> 00:06:37,141
People realize after the fact they're doing something wrong.

154
00:06:37,802 --> 00:06:38,502
And the question is,

155
00:06:38,642 --> 00:06:40,844
what does the developer do here as a company?

156
00:06:42,745 --> 00:06:43,906
Let's start with ESRB.

157
00:06:45,087 --> 00:06:46,688
What does Drawn Out Chess have to do

158
00:06:46,728 --> 00:06:47,769
to comply with the ratings?

159
00:06:48,149 --> 00:06:49,631
Well, if they're ESRB rated,

160
00:06:49,911 --> 00:06:51,152
they have to include that sticker.

161
00:06:51,732 --> 00:06:52,873
But in my hypothetical,

162
00:06:53,113 --> 00:06:55,615
this game is actually only being released on Steam and iOS.

163
00:06:56,797 --> 00:06:59,557
And what that means is they don't need an ESRB rating at all.

164
00:07:00,457 --> 00:07:03,538
Most games published today are not rated by the ESRB

165
00:07:04,038 --> 00:07:06,639
because neither Steam nor the App Store

166
00:07:06,679 --> 00:07:07,899
require that the games be rated.

167
00:07:07,919 --> 00:07:11,760
Okay, so what about for Apple?

168
00:07:12,020 --> 00:07:13,680
Well, for Apple, there needs to be a disclosure

169
00:07:13,700 --> 00:07:15,321
by item type like I talked about.

170
00:07:15,341 --> 00:07:18,581
So that means ShadyCorp needs to divide their items

171
00:07:18,621 --> 00:07:20,942
into categories and list those percentage odds

172
00:07:20,982 --> 00:07:21,762
for the players.

173
00:07:22,882 --> 00:07:24,843
They can't actually formally backtrack.

174
00:07:25,767 --> 00:07:28,628
Apple says that the disclosure has to be before the purchase.

175
00:07:29,168 --> 00:07:31,029
So there's actually no way to become compliant here.

176
00:07:31,509 --> 00:07:33,230
And somewhat frustratingly, Apple

177
00:07:33,270 --> 00:07:35,631
doesn't have formal rules for what you do when you mess up.

178
00:07:36,891 --> 00:07:39,733
So my best advice to ShadyCorp here would be fix the game,

179
00:07:40,033 --> 00:07:42,474
start disclosing in advance, and then do nothing else.

180
00:07:43,094 --> 00:07:45,975
And then if Apple comes talking to you, apologize,

181
00:07:46,075 --> 00:07:48,016
negotiate with them, work out a solution.

182
00:07:48,776 --> 00:07:50,617
But there's actually no formal process

183
00:07:50,657 --> 00:07:51,898
for how to remedy a violation.

184
00:07:54,722 --> 00:07:56,304
Okay, here are some takeaways.

185
00:07:56,844 --> 00:07:58,746
I know it's sometimes helpful to sort of have bullet points.

186
00:07:58,826 --> 00:08:00,387
Feel free to take photos of these slides.

187
00:08:00,807 --> 00:08:05,231
Takeaways for US regulation are ESRB requires disclosure,

188
00:08:05,932 --> 00:08:07,613
but there's no requirement that your game

189
00:08:08,274 --> 00:08:09,955
actually have an ESRB rating

190
00:08:10,336 --> 00:08:12,137
for most online sale platforms.

191
00:08:13,018 --> 00:08:15,400
All iOS games must disclose odds by item type.

192
00:08:16,221 --> 00:08:18,183
That disclosure must be prior to purchase.

193
00:08:19,023 --> 00:08:20,945
And there's no regulation on loot boxes,

194
00:08:21,105 --> 00:08:22,807
but that doesn't mean other laws don't apply.

195
00:08:26,433 --> 00:08:27,494
So now let's talk about the EU.

196
00:08:28,295 --> 00:08:31,397
So in the EU right now, there's country-specific regulation.

197
00:08:31,938 --> 00:08:33,419
That means every country in the EU

198
00:08:33,439 --> 00:08:34,840
gets to make up their own decision.

199
00:08:35,561 --> 00:08:38,102
Some countries, Germany, France, even PEGI,

200
00:08:38,143 --> 00:08:40,644
which is the equivalent of the ESRB in the EU,

201
00:08:41,345 --> 00:08:43,807
have called for EU-wide regulation,

202
00:08:44,367 --> 00:08:45,628
but right now we haven't seen any of it.

203
00:08:46,529 --> 00:08:48,831
So that means right now, other than two countries,

204
00:08:49,131 --> 00:08:50,812
you can do whatever you want in the EU,

205
00:08:50,932 --> 00:08:52,073
just like in the United States.

206
00:08:53,467 --> 00:08:56,510
The two countries that have rules are Belgium and Holland.

207
00:08:57,530 --> 00:09:00,353
In Belgium, it's illegal to have any acquirable item

208
00:09:00,773 --> 00:09:01,874
where chance is involved.

209
00:09:02,354 --> 00:09:05,617
So Belgium defines loot boxes as the purchase with real money

210
00:09:06,918 --> 00:09:08,439
or with paid virtual currency.

211
00:09:08,479 --> 00:09:10,560
That's sort of like the green gems, the premium currency

212
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:13,243
in your games, and where chance is involved.

213
00:09:13,543 --> 00:09:15,264
So you can sell items directly to players,

214
00:09:15,524 --> 00:09:18,306
but you can't sell these sort of randomized loot boxes.

215
00:09:19,981 --> 00:09:21,422
Holland is actually a little more permissive.

216
00:09:22,143 --> 00:09:24,685
Holland makes it illegal where the item is

217
00:09:24,745 --> 00:09:27,107
acquirable with real money, where there's

218
00:09:27,167 --> 00:09:30,230
chance involved, and where the final prize is transferable.

219
00:09:31,491 --> 00:09:33,253
So you actually have some more options in Holland.

220
00:09:33,613 --> 00:09:35,255
Oftentimes, the two countries get lumped together.

221
00:09:35,515 --> 00:09:36,756
But I think it's actually much easier

222
00:09:36,776 --> 00:09:38,638
to operate in Holland than it is in Belgium.

223
00:09:40,399 --> 00:09:41,741
So we'll continue our hypothetical.

224
00:09:42,201 --> 00:09:45,004
Shady Corp expands its drawn-out chess offerings to Europe.

225
00:09:45,584 --> 00:09:46,745
What do they need to do and where?

226
00:09:47,909 --> 00:09:49,490
Well, the answer for most countries is simple.

227
00:09:50,191 --> 00:09:51,072
They don't need to do anything.

228
00:09:53,314 --> 00:09:58,679
For Belgium, the answer is they probably need to put a geofence on the purchase of their

229
00:09:58,699 --> 00:10:00,520
loot boxes.

230
00:10:00,540 --> 00:10:04,884
They can publish their game, but they can't have those purchasable loot boxes in the game.

231
00:10:06,286 --> 00:10:08,228
For Holland, ShadyCorp has another option.

232
00:10:08,428 --> 00:10:10,610
They could either geofence the purchase of the loot box.

233
00:10:11,680 --> 00:10:16,586
Or they could prohibit players who have IP addresses in Holland from transferring their

234
00:10:16,646 --> 00:10:16,926
items.

235
00:10:17,848 --> 00:10:22,153
So you could still have those loot boxes in your game as long as the player can't transfer.

236
00:10:22,554 --> 00:10:27,160
And oftentimes it's more profitable to restrict the transfer of the items after the fact than

237
00:10:27,200 --> 00:10:28,982
to restrict the outlight purchase of loot boxes.

238
00:10:30,535 --> 00:10:34,039
I think what these different regulations highlight, and this may become more important in the

239
00:10:34,079 --> 00:10:39,205
future if we see other jurisdictions implementing regulations, and this is my third bullet

240
00:10:39,245 --> 00:10:43,430
point on these takeaways here, is that when you as a developer or publisher are building

241
00:10:43,450 --> 00:10:49,417
your game, you want to make sure every feature of your game can be toggled on and off, or

242
00:10:49,477 --> 00:10:51,199
at least every monetization feature.

243
00:10:52,119 --> 00:10:54,600
Because if you're in a position where you can't turn off

244
00:10:54,620 --> 00:10:56,501
the sale of loot boxes, then that

245
00:10:56,561 --> 00:10:58,642
means you just can't sell your game at all in these countries.

246
00:10:59,022 --> 00:11:00,582
You're limiting yourself from a market that

247
00:11:00,642 --> 00:11:02,823
might still be profitable despite the regulations.

248
00:11:03,604 --> 00:11:05,264
So as you're building your game, build

249
00:11:05,304 --> 00:11:06,865
with these considerations in mind

250
00:11:07,165 --> 00:11:08,806
that there are rules that are different by country

251
00:11:08,846 --> 00:11:10,666
and that those rules may change over time.

252
00:11:11,627 --> 00:11:13,628
Other big takeaways are, in Holland, you have a choice.

253
00:11:13,728 --> 00:11:16,169
You can restrict the transfer or the sale of loot boxes.

254
00:11:16,949 --> 00:11:19,670
In Belgium, you have to restrict the sale of randomized items

255
00:11:19,710 --> 00:11:20,250
for purchase.

256
00:11:21,464 --> 00:11:25,426
And then sort of my final point is I've seen these calls for EU-wide regulation.

257
00:11:25,446 --> 00:11:30,668
I don't expect it to happen soon, although you ask 100 lawyers and you get 100 different

258
00:11:30,708 --> 00:11:31,329
opinions on that.

259
00:11:33,750 --> 00:11:38,552
So so far, the sort of takeaway has been there's not a lot of regulation and it's pretty easy

260
00:11:38,572 --> 00:11:39,172
to get around it.

261
00:11:40,393 --> 00:11:41,593
China is sort of a different story.

262
00:11:42,679 --> 00:11:47,163
In China, loot boxes are regulated by two different organizations, one with a focus

263
00:11:47,203 --> 00:11:51,307
on content and the other with a focus on monetization and mechanics.

264
00:11:52,388 --> 00:11:55,331
We're going to start by going through the formal rules and then we'll talk about sort

265
00:11:55,351 --> 00:11:56,912
of how that ends up working in practice.

266
00:11:58,273 --> 00:12:03,658
So formally on the monetization, you cannot have a randomized event, right?

267
00:12:03,818 --> 00:12:06,301
China defines a loot box as any randomized event.

268
00:12:07,192 --> 00:12:09,133
That seems a little overbroad, doesn't it?

269
00:12:09,173 --> 00:12:11,193
That seems like everything I put up on that first slide

270
00:12:11,213 --> 00:12:12,274
in the presentation today.

271
00:12:12,774 --> 00:12:14,234
But you can't have a randomized event

272
00:12:14,274 --> 00:12:16,455
for purchase with real money or virtual currency.

273
00:12:17,455 --> 00:12:18,775
This might be a translation issue.

274
00:12:18,915 --> 00:12:20,076
I think virtual currency actually

275
00:12:20,096 --> 00:12:21,316
means paid virtual currency.

276
00:12:22,076 --> 00:12:24,917
We haven't really seen any enforcement against games

277
00:12:24,957 --> 00:12:26,897
where you just have the gold you collect naturally

278
00:12:26,917 --> 00:12:27,657
through gameplay.

279
00:12:28,698 --> 00:12:30,738
But formally, it says any virtual currency.

280
00:12:30,798 --> 00:12:33,159
So as written and as translated into English,

281
00:12:33,539 --> 00:12:35,379
that could be even the currency you only

282
00:12:35,399 --> 00:12:36,300
can earn through gameplay.

283
00:12:37,799 --> 00:12:40,541
Second rule is the virtual items or services that you offer

284
00:12:40,981 --> 00:12:42,362
have to be obtainable by other means.

285
00:12:43,703 --> 00:12:44,423
What are other means?

286
00:12:44,903 --> 00:12:46,384
That could mean that you could get it through gameplay,

287
00:12:46,404 --> 00:12:47,725
you could get it through randomized drops

288
00:12:47,765 --> 00:12:48,986
from killing monsters in the game.

289
00:12:49,426 --> 00:12:51,167
You could have it so that the only way to get the item

290
00:12:51,207 --> 00:12:52,788
is to purchase it outright from the store

291
00:12:53,108 --> 00:12:53,948
or get a loot box.

292
00:12:54,449 --> 00:12:57,230
So you can still have items that are only purchasable

293
00:12:57,370 --> 00:12:57,971
through real money,

294
00:12:58,271 --> 00:13:00,452
but there has to be some other way to get that item.

295
00:13:02,662 --> 00:13:04,984
And then the third requirement is no compulsion loops.

296
00:13:05,685 --> 00:13:07,487
These are like sort of Skinner box mechanics.

297
00:13:08,468 --> 00:13:11,131
We'll talk about in our hypothetical for this country

298
00:13:11,611 --> 00:13:13,914
about what that might look like even in the context

299
00:13:13,954 --> 00:13:15,916
where you weren't directly selling the loot boxes.

300
00:13:18,278 --> 00:13:18,819
But that's not all.

301
00:13:20,120 --> 00:13:21,862
China has regulations on disclosures

302
00:13:22,683 --> 00:13:24,945
and these are super onerous regulations.

303
00:13:26,090 --> 00:13:30,612
The first is you need to provide information about the odds for your loot box up front.

304
00:13:31,433 --> 00:13:33,914
And that information is not like Apple where it's by type.

305
00:13:34,695 --> 00:13:38,157
You're formally supposed to list your odds of getting every single item in that loot

306
00:13:38,197 --> 00:13:38,517
box.

307
00:13:39,177 --> 00:13:42,419
Now, that may just mean that you're taking the number of items that are in a category

308
00:13:42,479 --> 00:13:47,822
and dividing that category percentage to list them, but, you know, it is a more formal requirement.

309
00:13:49,043 --> 00:13:52,344
But not only do you have to list your odds in advance.

310
00:13:53,305 --> 00:13:55,067
Those odds have to be transparent to users.

311
00:13:55,728 --> 00:14:00,013
That means it's easy for a Chinese user to find those odds.

312
00:14:00,333 --> 00:14:03,217
Can't be complicated, can't be at the very bottom of your page,

313
00:14:03,257 --> 00:14:04,418
click here to see the odds.

314
00:14:04,979 --> 00:14:07,642
Basically, if they run a search for those odds,

315
00:14:07,702 --> 00:14:08,763
they should be able to find them.

316
00:14:10,400 --> 00:14:13,420
And then the final requirement, which is incredibly labor

317
00:14:13,460 --> 00:14:17,281
intensive, is that every game is supposed to keep for 90

318
00:14:17,682 --> 00:14:21,362
days and publicly make available the results of every

319
00:14:21,442 --> 00:14:23,223
single loot box outcome in their game.

320
00:14:24,343 --> 00:14:27,904
Thousands or millions of outcomes kept in a chart, and

321
00:14:27,924 --> 00:14:29,364
it's supposed to be publicly available.

322
00:14:30,105 --> 00:14:33,245
Now you might be thinking to yourself, well, I bet you 50

323
00:14:34,066 --> 00:14:37,466
bucks, you can't find a single company operating in China

324
00:14:37,486 --> 00:14:38,027
that does that.

325
00:14:38,810 --> 00:14:40,351
And if you're thinking that, you'd be up $50.

326
00:14:42,672 --> 00:14:45,994
I searched through the top 20 licensed games in China,

327
00:14:46,394 --> 00:14:47,655
and I wasn't able to find it.

328
00:14:48,075 --> 00:14:49,736
And so then I called my colleague in Hong Kong.

329
00:14:49,756 --> 00:14:51,296
I said, look, maybe it's a language barrier.

330
00:14:51,957 --> 00:14:54,078
And my colleague in Hong Kong couldn't find a single game

331
00:14:54,118 --> 00:14:54,778
that did that either.

332
00:14:56,119 --> 00:14:58,500
So I think what you see in China is a lot of rules,

333
00:14:59,261 --> 00:15:01,862
but really inconsistent enforcement of those rules.

334
00:15:03,463 --> 00:15:04,844
And the truth is, whether or not you

335
00:15:04,864 --> 00:15:06,485
can offer a loot box in China depends

336
00:15:06,525 --> 00:15:07,705
on whether the government likes your game.

337
00:15:11,288 --> 00:15:13,569
So now we're going to come into today's last hypothetical.

338
00:15:14,610 --> 00:15:16,932
And this has to do with dynamic odds adjustment.

339
00:15:17,452 --> 00:15:20,454
So it's March, and Shady Corp's game is doing well,

340
00:15:20,494 --> 00:15:21,474
but they want it to do better.

341
00:15:21,494 --> 00:15:25,217
And so they're going to engage in dynamic odds adjustment.

342
00:15:25,437 --> 00:15:26,218
What do I mean by that?

343
00:15:26,238 --> 00:15:30,360
That means adjusting the odds of the outcomes for your loot box

344
00:15:31,381 --> 00:15:33,802
in the hopes of denying the player what they really want,

345
00:15:34,163 --> 00:15:35,784
so they keep buying more loot boxes.

346
00:15:36,583 --> 00:15:38,164
This can target a specific player.

347
00:15:38,464 --> 00:15:40,365
We might have data and metrics that tell us

348
00:15:40,405 --> 00:15:41,326
about an individual player.

349
00:15:42,206 --> 00:15:45,347
But that sort of odds adjustment can be done on a wider basis.

350
00:15:46,108 --> 00:15:47,388
So in our example, it's March.

351
00:15:48,208 --> 00:15:49,709
St. Patrick's Day was Sunday.

352
00:15:49,729 --> 00:15:52,770
And ShadyCorp realizes their players really

353
00:15:52,810 --> 00:15:55,632
want to play with their St. Patrick's Day-themed chess set.

354
00:15:56,812 --> 00:15:59,473
And so previously, when you got one of their legendary chess

355
00:15:59,493 --> 00:16:01,714
sets, there was an even chance of getting a pirate chess set,

356
00:16:01,754 --> 00:16:03,995
a ninja chess set, a Halloween chess set.

357
00:16:05,585 --> 00:16:06,866
but they're gonna adjust the odds

358
00:16:06,926 --> 00:16:09,327
so the odds of getting that St. Patrick's Day chess set

359
00:16:09,367 --> 00:16:09,867
go down.

360
00:16:11,188 --> 00:16:12,368
And not only are they gonna do that,

361
00:16:12,709 --> 00:16:15,430
they realize no one wants a Halloween chess set in March.

362
00:16:16,090 --> 00:16:18,211
So they're gonna increase the odds of that chess set.

363
00:16:18,611 --> 00:16:20,672
And the hope here is that the players

364
00:16:20,732 --> 00:16:21,633
don't get what they want,

365
00:16:22,173 --> 00:16:23,974
and so they keep purchasing more loot boxes.

366
00:16:25,975 --> 00:16:27,555
So let's talk globally.

367
00:16:28,336 --> 00:16:29,416
Is this practice legal?

368
00:16:29,696 --> 00:16:31,677
What does ShadyCorp have to do to make it legal?

369
00:16:33,118 --> 00:16:34,619
Well, in the United States.

370
00:16:35,430 --> 00:16:37,372
Yeah, currently you can do this.

371
00:16:38,714 --> 00:16:43,999
Even Apple's terms, right, only require disclosure of those top-level categories.

372
00:16:44,780 --> 00:16:49,325
And here ShadyCorp isn't changing the odds of getting a legendary item, they're just

